        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For a given GMC mass, diameter and velocity width we estimate the expected 230 
GHz line flux using L_CO = M/3.68 (K km/s pc2) where we adopt a Galactic X_CO 
and assume approximately equal line strengths at 115 and 230 GHz. Since 
L_CO=3.26E7 SdV (D_Mpc/nu_obs)^2, we solve for (Sdv) for the cloud. Dividing 
by the cloud's velocity width and number of synthesized beams per cloud we 
deduce the average expected line flux density. We also consider that the 
nuclear ring's diameter places most of the emission at or within the 76% 
sensitivity radius, so the line flux densities (and required rms) we derive 
for a given cloud must be scaled by 0.76.

The least massive GMC we consider has M = 10^4.5 M_solar, d = 13 pc,(i.e.,
unresolved) and width 2.2 km/s. Using the L_CO relations above we would 
expect a 230 GHz line flux of 113.4 mJy km/s for the entire cloud. At 11.1 
Mpc the cloud subtends 0.25", equal to our requested natural weighted 
synthesized beam. We expect f=51.4 mJy within one beam, or 39 mJy due to 
the location within the 12m primary beam. A 10-sigma detection - required 
for accurate cloud property determinations - requires an rms of 3.9 mJy. This 
can be reached in 1.33-hours (including calibration and overheads) with 
0.75 km/s bandwidth according to the ALMA OT, which is adequate velocity 
resolution for the GMC's linewidth.Note that GMCs that are resolved in
velocity but not spatially will be important for testing the CO
luminosity-velocity width Larson relation.

For a typical GMC (M = 10^5 M_solar, d = 25 pc, dV = 5 km/s) we expect a 
230 GHz line flux integral of 359 mJy km/s following the above steps. Given the 
angular size of the cloud at 11.1 Mpc there will be 3.5 synthesized beams 
covering it. Dividing the line flux integral by (3.5 x 5 km/s) gives an 
expected line flux density per beam of 21 mJy, requiring a 2.1 mJy rms for a 
10-sigma detection. However, because of the ring's position in the primary beam
the expected flux density per beam and rms become 15.6 mJy and 1.6 mJy 
respectively. For a channel width of 1 km/s this rms can be reached in 
2.19-hours. 

For a very massive GMC (M = 3 x 10^6 M_solar, d = 100 pc, dV = 13 km/s) and 
following the above steps, we expect an average 230 GHz line flux density per 
beam of 12 mJy after accounting for the ring's location within the primary 
beam, requiring an rms of 1.2 mJy for a 10-sigma detection. This can be reached
in 2.19-hours (including calibration and overheads) using 2 km/s channel width.

We will have considerable flexibility in averaging channels and beam 
parameters in making channel maps which will aid our detection
and characterization of GMC properties. We request 2.2-hours of time in total.

We note that the largest recoverable structure will be around 6".
This exceeds the nuclear ring's width. Since the ring's width place
a natural constraint on the maximum diameter of its GMCs we are
confident that we will recover the bulk of their CO emission.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
